{"sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"level":2,"type":"heading","text":"","anchor":""},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Some of the functions in this package should be considered “instance methods”. If tuples were a named type, we could extend them with real methods that incorporate dot syntax."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"For example, to add 1 to a tuple of integers, we’d ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"like"}]},{"text":" to be able to write:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["let tuple = (1, 2, 3)","tuple.map { $0 + 1 }"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"…but the best we can do is:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["map(tuple)() { $0 + 1 }"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"level":4,"type":"heading","text":"Recommended Mental Model for “Tuple Instance Methods”: Unsugared Instance Methods","anchor":"Recommended-Mental-Model-for-Tuple-Instance-Methods-Unsugared-Instance-Methods"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Say that we want to use "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collection\/map(_:)"},{"type":"text","text":" on an "},{"code":"Int Array","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". Because ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"text":" is a named type, Swift provides that functionality using this syntax:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["[1, 2, 3].map { $0 + 1 }"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But this is sugar for what’s really going on. Swift’s "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"instance"}]},{"type":"text","text":" methods are actually "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"type"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" methods, which accept an instance as their argument, and return a closure. We typically think of this closure as the instance method itself.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To illustrate this, here’s an ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"text":" extension:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["extension Array {","  func method() { }","}"],"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You’d normally call that using this syntax:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let instance = [1, 2, 3]","instance.method()"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But it’s also available as a "},{"code":"static","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method, on "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"text":", and can alternatively be called like this:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["Array.method(instance)()"],"type":"codeListing"},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"map","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" from the standard library can similarly be called like so:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["Array.map(instance)() { $0 + 1 }"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"That’s how the package authors think about the functions cataloged below.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"aside","name":"Note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It’s unfortunately not possible to remove the “"},{"code":"()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"” before trailing closures without access to "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"real","type":"text"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" instance methods. The limitation has been logged as a bug for years.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"note"}],"kind":"content"}],"topicSections":[{"anchor":"Topics","identifiers":["doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/appending(_:)","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/prepending(_:)","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/callAsFunction(_:)","doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-\/repeat(_:)"]